Train, Test Split¶

Train test split is a model validation procedure that allows you to simulate how a model would perform on new/unseen data.

Why do we split our data¶

To avoid overfitting. Overfitting is a modeling error when a function is too closely aligned to a limited set of data points. As a result, the model is useful in reference only to its initial data set, and not to any other data sets.

When our model is overfitted (like the image below), it is likely to perform worse on new data.

The process¶

Once we have loaded our data, there are four steps:

  1. Arrange the data into Features and Targets
  2. Split the data into a training dataset and a testing dataset
  3. Train the model using the training dataset. This is X_train and y_train in the image.
  4. Test the model on the testing set (X_test and y_test in the image) and evaluate the performance.

Links¶

Statology has some great python guides. There is one specifcally on How to Create a Train and Test Set from a Pandas DataFrame

Understanding Train Test Split

Terminology¶

  • Training dataset - The sample of data used to fit the model.
  • Test dataset - The sample of data used to provide an unbiased evaluation of a final model fit on the training dataset.
  • Validation dataset - The sample of data used to provide an unbiased evaluation of a model fit on the training dataset while tuning model hyperparameters. The evaluation becomes more biased as skill on the validation dataset is incorporated into the model configuration.

Note: In this session we are only focusing on training and testing datasets.

Split the data into Train and Test¶

Now we will split our data into a training dataset and a testing dataset. Our training dataset will be 70% of our data, whiile our testing dataset will be 30%.

In [5]:
# Call the train_test_split function to split our Features and Target datasets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(golf_features, golf_target, test_size=0.3, random_state = 1)

The Train Test Split Function - Optional¶

The train_test_split function is provided by the model_selection subpackage available under the sklearn package. The function receives as input the following parameters:

  • arrays — the datasets to be split;
  • test_size — the size of the test set. It could be either a float or an integer number. If it is a float, it should be a number between 0.0 and 1.0 and represents the proportion of the dataset to include in the test set. If it is an integer, it is the total number of samples to include in the test set. If the test_size is not set, the value is set automatically to the complement of the train size;
  • train_size — the size of the train set. Its behavior is complementary to the test_size variable;
  • random_state — before applying to split, the dataset is shuffled. The random_state variable is an integer that initializes the seed used for shuffling. It is used to make the experiment reproducible;
  • shuffle — it specifies whether to shuffle data before splitting or not. The default value is True;
  • stratify — if not None, it specifies an array of frequencies for class labels. This permits the splitting phase the preserve the frequency of class labels as specified.

#calculate metrics
acc = accuracy_score(eval_class["y_actual"], eval_class["y_predicted"]) # Accuracy Score
prec = precision_score(eval_class["y_actual"], eval_class["y_predicted"]) # Precision Score
rec = recall_score(eval_class["y_actual"], eval_class["y_predicted"]) # Recall Score
f1 = f1_score(eval_class["y_actual"], eval_class["y_predicted"]) # F1 score
cm = confusion_matrix(eval_class["y_actual"], eval_class["y_predicted"]) # Confusion Matrix

# Create the confusion matrix display
display_matrix = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm)
In [9]:
# print metrics
print(f'Accuracy is {acc:.3f}')
print(f'Precision is {prec:.3f}')
print(f'Recall is {rec:.3f}')
print(f'F1 is {f1:.3f}')

#display confusion matrix
display_matrix.plot()

This website gives a good explanation of the regression evaluation metrics. MAE, MSE, RMSE, Coefficient of Determination, Adjusted R Squared — Which Metric is Better

In [11]:
#calculate regression metrics
mae = mean_absolute_error(eval_reg["y_actual"], eval_reg["y_predicted"]) # Mean Absolute Error
mse = mean_squared_error(eval_reg["y_actual"], eval_reg["y_predicted"]) # Mean Squared Error
# To get the RMSE we call the  mean_squared_error function but pass it squared = False 
rmse = mean_squared_error(eval_reg["y_actual"], eval_reg["y_predicted"], squared = False) # Root Mean Squared Error
In [12]:
print(f'MAE is {mae:.3f}')
print(f'MSE is {mse:.3f}')
print(f'RMSE is {rmse:.3f}')
